Decisions

Purpose:
- Public-safe current decision memory for active product, architecture, documentation, and claim-boundary choices.

Verification status: active operational memory; verify against code, docs, and reports before relying on it.
Memory scope: governing decisions that should steer future agents until explicitly changed.
Public-safe status: safe for source control; contains no credential values.
Update route: update this local file when governing decisions change; submit durable public-safe decision summaries to https://memoryendpoints.com/api/matm/memory-events/submit when authenticated.
Source of truth: current repository state, `.uai/totem.uai`, `AGENTS.md`, `docs/reports/final-readiness-report.md`, and user instructions.
Next action for agents: preserve these decisions unless current code, reports, or direct human instruction supersedes them.
Must not expose: raw API keys, bearer tokens, FTP credentials, database passwords, private keys, private handoff payloads, raw one-time keys, or private deployment values.

Current governing decisions:
- Keep `E:\MemoryEndpoints.com` as the single source of truth for MemoryEndpoints.com and MultiAgentMemory.com content.
- Keep local `.uai` active always. Hosted MATM augments `.uai`; it does not replace it.
- Keep active `.uai` date-free active operational memory only.
- Do not add `.uai` files named `short-term-memory.uai`, `active-memory.uai`, `current-state.uai`, `project-state.uai`, `working-state.uai`, or equivalent under any purpose or interpretation.
- Store deep detail in docs, reports, MATM records, or other durable targets, then point to those from typed `.uai` files.
- Store company, workspace, and project knowledge trees as protected database records, not as generated filesystem trees. Filesystem reports can be temporary evidence or source input, but crawlable/searchable company knowledge belongs in the database source of truth.
- Never expose a password-free public wiki or public knowledge index. The `/knowledge` page is an empty authentication shell until a workspace key succeeds; wiki trees, pages, search results, and external-link records remain protected and tenant-isolated.
- Use the MemoryEndpoints.com home page as the public inbound address. Public discovery files may describe public-safe capabilities and authentication orientation, but they must not enumerate tenant knowledge, private deep routes, workspace identifiers, or protected full-context exports.
- Treat accounts/users as identity and company-membership principals only, never as knowledge ownership scopes. Account-company membership is many-to-many; companies own workspaces, workspaces own projects, and durable knowledge is scoped only to company, workspace, or project.
- Treat `docs/` as transitional migration/evidence material only. After the knowledge is moved deliberately into MemoryEndpoints.com, `docs/` should not remain as a parallel source-of-truth documentation tree.
- Do not bulk-import report archives into company knowledge. Ingest reports deliberately through reviewed, source-notated database document writes so scope, category, project placement, and context are correct.
- Process one source report at a time, but do not force a multi-topic report into one oversized page. Preserve the canonical source, then create semantically bounded pages with explicit source provenance so retrieval remains focused without losing evidence.
- When a source mixes durable principles with stale, unsafe, vendor-specific, or overclaimed guidance, write a reviewer-authored current synthesis with preserved source hashes instead of labeling the raw source section current.
- Treat taxonomy paths as first-class wiki navigation. Each knowledge document needs title, description, keywords, and one or more hierarchy paths; multiple hierarchy placement is expected when a concept belongs in more than one context.
- Treat knowledge lifecycle and authority as first-class database fields. Non-current pages require an explicit reason; superseded pages require a database relation to the current replacement; search must expose warnings and rank current canonical knowledge ahead of stale guidance.
- Review and promote each source-backed memory individually. A promoted historical or proposed memory keeps that lifecycle meaning; promotion makes it durable and retrievable but never converts it into a current implementation claim.
- Treat MCP, moderation models, alternate graph stores, trigger systems, rotating credentials, PaaS automation, container updaters, and SQLite replication as optional candidates until an explicit architecture decision and implementation evidence exist. Vendor features and model consensus never supersede tenant authorization, database provenance, human accountability, recovery testing, or honest capability claims.
- Use the smallest agent topology that a task justifies. Add agents only for an explicit decomposition, independent-evidence, concurrency, review, or tool-specialization benefit, and measure quality, cost, elapsed time, conflicts, rework, and verification against a simpler single-agent baseline.
- Keep deterministic authorization, idempotency, state transitions, conflict detection, timeouts, retries, and completion gates outside model consensus. Humans and accountable organizational leaders retain authority for policy, credentials, destructive operations, production releases, disputed review, recovery, escalation, and shutdown.
- Treat shared-memory concurrency as an architecture contract. Read-only context, append-only evidence, reviewed durable knowledge, mutable current state, and private working memory have different owners and conflict rules; never use an unversioned destructive rewrite as a generic collaboration primitive.
- Treat backups, replication, failover, container updates, confidential computing, and model moderation as bounded controls rather than guarantees. Require database-specific coverage, restore and rollback proof, staged releases, measured classifier behavior, explicit threat models, and human escalation; do not use unmaintained or production-disclaimed update tooling for production automation.
- Treat UAI-1 as a portable public exchange and evidence contract that can complement MCP, A2A, OpenAPI, JSON Schema, identity systems, and tracing without replacing their runtime, transport, tool, coordination, validation, authentication, or authorization responsibilities.
- Treat capability levels, UAI declarations, schema conformance, signatures, DIDs, credentials, and public profiles as bounded evidence under their own contracts. None grants company membership, workspace or project access, mutation authority, network access, provider access, execution permission, or truth by itself.
- Keep UAIX Project Handoff, Agent File Handoff, AGENTS.md, and local `.uai` in their actual roles: portable repository context and reviewed intake. AGENTS.md has no universal required section schema, dropped files remain untrusted, and no handoff format authorizes automatic execution or bulk import.
- Preserve product boundaries. LocalEndpoints.com public behavior is metadata and validation while approved local execution belongs to its desktop boundary; Carcinus owns its versioned public-profile, one-time write-token, and restore contracts; NeuralWikis remains a separate public exchange; MemoryEndpoints owns protected durable company, workspace, and project memory.
- Do not add arbitrary agent-code, shell, container, microVM, WebAssembly, MCP-tool, or uploaded-file execution to the MemoryEndpoints application process. Any future execution plane needs its own named owner, repository, deployment, identity and credential boundary, threat model, authorization policy, isolation design, recovery plan, and acceptance evidence.
- Choose hardened containers, gVisor, microVMs, WebAssembly, or hosted sandboxes from the workload and threat model rather than a universal ranking. Isolation is defense in depth, Docker is neither categorically adequate nor inadequate, and no sandbox brand supports impenetrable, absolute, zero-risk, or guaranteed-safe claims.
- Treat safe no-op as no side effect plus a typed, explainable, auditable, and reviewable failure. Never report silent success, hide a permanent denial, execute truncated commands, or let schema validity, UAI conformance, MCP metadata, signatures, static analysis, anomaly scores, or model judgment grant authority.
- Treat restored snapshots and persistent workspaces as supply-chain inputs that can preserve compromise. Require provenance, ownership, quarantine, policy and malware checks, versioning, retention, revocation, and tested restore behavior before reuse.
- Default unconfigured local runtime storage to SQLite, use verified MySQL/MariaDB in production, and never use JSON files as the durable knowledge source of truth.
- Treat every retained external URL as its own canonical data type with URL, host, site name, page title, description, keywords, review state, and crawl state. Connect it to knowledge pages through contextual citation records; do not rely on raw URLs embedded only in report text.
- External-link upsert is metadata indexing, not permission to crawl. Reject non-public hosts and credential-bearing URLs, and require a separate reviewed crawl decision before fetching remote content.
- Treat user-agent strings, bot labels, inline page instructions, discovery manifests, and crawler identifiers as untrusted hints or telemetry, never authentication or authorization.
- Treat availability and crawlability as point-in-time evidence. Invalid or sentinel access dates do not establish observation time, and a failed request does not prove a blanket WAF; record the actual DNS, TLS, redirect, HTTP, media-type, body-parse, authentication, and client-environment result before making a current claim.
- Treat `llms.txt` as an optional orientation proposal, `robots.txt` as cooperative crawler policy, sitemaps as public URL inventories, and CORS as browser response-sharing behavior. None grants protected access, and wildcard CORS is not a compatibility shortcut for credential-dependent tenant responses.
- Do not describe arbitrary `/.well-known/` OpenAPI or MCP files, custom manifests, routers, MATM profiles, or agent pointers as universal standards. Use protocol-defined discovery only when that protocol is implemented and tested; otherwise identify the path as a product convention.
- Do not copy public NeuralWikis wiki content, branding, or generated public site material.
- Do not claim certification, endorsement, hidden credential validation, automatic repository writes, or live production database support that is not actually verified.
- Keep UAIX wizard fragment URLs as UAIX setup-option references only; they do not change the MemoryEndpoints home-page inbound rule.
- Keep README files as human repository or site documentation only. Do not use README files as active `.uai` memory, handoff-bucket guidance, or intake completion evidence.
- Keep human and agent representations on one protected company/workspace/project knowledge graph. Human accessibility, meaningful links, and readable context remain security and operations requirements; machine-readable routes complement rather than replace them.
- Treat `robots.txt` as crawl preference, `llms.txt` as optional public-safe orientation, and AI manifests, hashes, selectors, JSON-LD, user-agent strings, and custom hints as non-authoritative evidence. None authenticates a caller, authorizes tenant access, proves trust, or permits a public protected-context export.
- Describe HTTP behavior with current OpenAPI and structured problem details where appropriate. Bind idempotency to tenant, principal, operation, and request fingerprint with concurrency and readback semantics; the `Idempotency-Key` header remains an application contract rather than a current RFC.
- Use machine-readable acceptance evidence, token and cost budgets, work-in-progress limits, and reviewer-capacity planning as additions to accountable empirical delivery. Agents do not inherit Product Owner, security approver, legal, or release authority.
